, who caricatured her in literary periodicals and romans à clef. Most notably, La Vaudère claimed to have written the Rêve d’Egypte pantomime, whose 1907 production at the Moulin Rouge featured a kiss between Missy and Colette that led to riots and the suspension of future performances. Larson scrutinizes the ensemble of these various media constructions, privileging La Vaudère’s self-representation in interviews and advertisements, and brings to light her agency in creating an image that captivated public attention and boosted sales of her writings.An engrossing examination of La Vaudère’s life and work, this volume probes the quandaries of scholarship seeking to responsibly recover lost female voices and makes a long-overdue contribution to nineteenth-century French literary studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 19th Century .2bisacsh  aBelle Époque.  aColette.  aDecadence.  aFin-de-siècle.  aFrench Feminism.  aFrench women writers.  aJane de la Vaudère.  aJeanne Scrive.  aLes Androgynes.  aLes Courtisanes de Brahma.  aLes Sataniques.  aNineteenth-Century.  aRêve d’Egypte.  amummies.  aplagiarism.  aracecars.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079775640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978027109475540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271094755423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271094755/original  a978-3-11-079775-6  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK